<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="401" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,151,752]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,223,248]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[331,551,224,248]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Barilius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="canarensis">
<emphasis box="[331,551,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">Barilius canarensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[812,921,224,248]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Barilius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ardens">
<emphasis box="[812,921,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">B. ardens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its unique colour pattern, consisting of a double row of spots along the length of the body, the first row with 
<number box="[945,1001,260,284]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="11.0" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="9.0">9–13</number>
round or oval bluish-green spots 
<number box="[1394,1436,260,284]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
scales high and 
<number box="[328,370,296,320]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
scales wide and the second row, with 
<number box="[798,839,296,320]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4</number>
smaller spots reaching up to the anal-fin origin (vs. a row of 
<number box="[231,272,332,356]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="8.0" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="7.0">7–9</number>
large, vertically-elongate, bluish-green blotches 
<number box="[818,860,332,357]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="5.0" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.0">4–6</number>
scales high and 
<number box="[1044,1085,332,356]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3</number>
scales wide along the length of the body, of which in large adults the first three blotches are fragmented into a smaller row of blotches: see 
<figureCitation box="[1360,1436,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1425,1447]" captionTargetBox="[229,1358,628,1398]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[229,1358,628,1399]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Barilius ardens, A, male, unregistered specimen in life, ~ 90 mm SL; B, juvenile unregistered specimen in life, ~ 20.6 mm SL; C, female, paratype, prior to fixation, ZSI / SRC, F. 8813, 85.5 mm SL." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242893/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">
Figs. 
<number box="[1422,1436,368,392]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
&amp; 
<figureCitation box="[181,196,404,428]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1829,1851]" captionTargetBox="[217,1369,805,1807]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[217,1369,805,1807]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Barilius canarensis, MKC 415, A, 83.7 mm SL; B, 81.9 mm SL." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242896/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">
<number box="[181,196,404,428]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
) Moreover, 
<taxonomicName box="[339,492,405,428]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Barilius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="canarensis">
<emphasis box="[339,492,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">B. canarensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[805,913,404,428]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Barilius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ardens">
<emphasis box="[805,913,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">B. ardens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its fifth ceratobranchial, which has 
<number box="[1362,1375,404,429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="5.0">5</number>
+ 
<number box="[1391,1406,404,429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="4.0">4</number>
+ 
<number box="[1422,1436,404,429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="2.0">2</number>
(vs. 
<number box="[200,213,439,464]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="5.0">5</number>
+ 
<number box="[230,245,439,464]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="4.0">4</number>
+ 
<number box="[261,274,439,464]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="3.0">3</number>
) teeth; by possessing 
<number box="[523,592,439,464]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="14.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="14.0">14–15</number>
(vs. 
<number box="[649,720,439,464]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="17.0" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="16.0">16–18</number>
) predorsal scales, and having the dorsal and anal fins margined with white (vs. broadly margined with bright orange: see 
<figureCitation box="[800,877,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1425,1447]" captionTargetBox="[229,1358,628,1398]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[229,1358,628,1399]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Barilius ardens, A, male, unregistered specimen in life, ~ 90 mm SL; B, juvenile unregistered specimen in life, ~ 20.6 mm SL; C, female, paratype, prior to fixation, ZSI / SRC, F. 8813, 85.5 mm SL." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242893/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">
Figs. 
<number box="[863,877,476,500]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
&amp; 
<figureCitation box="[914,931,476,500]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1829,1851]" captionTargetBox="[217,1369,805,1807]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[217,1369,805,1807]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Barilius canarensis, MKC 415, A, 83.7 mm SL; B, 81.9 mm SL." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242896/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">
<number box="[914,931,476,500]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[952,1104,477,500]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Barilius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="canarensis">
<emphasis box="[952,1104,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">B. canarensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Barilius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="malabaricus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">B. malabaricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having 
<number box="[423,450,511,536]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="10.0">10</number>
½ (vs. 
<number box="[532,558,511,536]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="11.0">11</number>
½) branched dorsal-fin rays and 
<number box="[935,962,511,536]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="13.0">13</number>
½ (vs. 
<number box="[1043,1070,511,536]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="14.0">14</number>
½– 
<number box="[1108,1134,511,536]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="15.0">15</number>
½) branched anal-fin rays, and having the dorsal and anal fins margined with white (vs. broadly margined with bright orange: see 
<figureCitation box="[1295,1371,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1829,1851]" captionTargetBox="[217,1369,805,1807]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[217,1369,805,1807]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Barilius canarensis, MKC 415, A, 83.7 mm SL; B, 81.9 mm SL." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242896/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">
Figs. 
<number box="[1357,1371,548,572]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
&amp; 
<figureCitation box="[1406,1422,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1845,1867]" captionTargetBox="[217,1369,553,1823]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[217,1369,553,1823]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Barilius malabaricus, A, unregistered specimen in life from aquarium trade ~ 80 mm SL, Kannur, Kerala; B, MKC 416, prior to fixation, 61.8 mm SL, Valapattanam river, Kerala; C, ZSI / SRC, F. 8816, prior to fixation, 76.8 mm SL, Payaswini River, Kerala." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242898/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">
<number box="[1406,1422,548,573]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[151,302,584,608]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Barilius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="canarensis">
<emphasis box="[151,302,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">B. canarensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[608,711,584,608]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Barilius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bakeri">
<emphasis box="[608,711,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">B. bakeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its unique colour pattern, consisting of a double row of spots along the length of the body, the first row with 
<number box="[707,762,620,644]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="11.0" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="9.0">9–13</number>
round or oval bluish-green spots 
<number box="[1156,1198,620,644]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
scales high and 
<number box="[1394,1436,620,644]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
scales wide and the second row, with 
<number box="[576,618,656,680]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4</number>
smaller spots reaching up to the anal-fin origin (vs. only a single row of spots along the length of the body); having 
<number box="[644,714,692,717]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="35.5" valueMax="36.0" valueMin="35.0">35–36</number>
+ 
<number box="[746,760,692,716]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="1.0">1</number>
(vs. 
<number box="[817,886,692,716]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="37.5" valueMax="38.0" valueMin="37.0">37–38</number>
+ 
<number box="[918,930,692,716]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="1.0">1</number>
) lateral line scales and slender, well-defined gill rakers (vs. fleshy, rudimentary gill rakers: see 
<figureCitation box="[714,807,727,752]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1262,1284]" captionTargetBox="[217,1369,517,1240]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[217,1369,517,1241]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 10. First gill arch, A, Barilius bakeri, MKC 384, 68.7 mm SL; B, B. canarensis, MKC 415, 63.4 mm SL (Scale bar = 2 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242902/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="401">
Figs. 
<number box="[776,807,728,752]" pageId="5" pageNumber="401" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
